\section{Abstract}
In this paper we work to formulate a satellite collection problem of the first 100 largest satellites by TLE data (gathered on celestrack) as a combinatorial optimization task under mission resource constraints. Given a catalog of orbital objects derived from Two-Line Element (TLE) data, the objective is to maximize the number of satellites that can be collected subject to a total mission cost budget. Mission cost is modeled as a function of distance (or proxy $\Delta V$) between a servicing spacecraft and candidate targets. The resulting problem is a 0--1 travelling salesman problem (TSP), which is NP-hard. We reformulate the constrained optimization problem into a Quadratic Unconstrained Binary Optimization (QUBO) form, enabling solution via quantum annealing or classical QUBO solvers. We attempted to analyze several approaches coming to a conclusion on the best solver to optimize this TSP. 

